The paper proposes a machine learning model for learning the structure and relationships between nodes in graphs, which is a common problem in many areas of computer science. Specifically, the model extends the Neural Turing Machine (NTM) to handle conditional transition graphs, which are graphs where transitions between nodes are conditioned on external information. This problem is relevant to several subfields of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), neural networks (cs.NE), natural language processing (cs.CL), and social networks (cs.SI). Therefore, these are the most likely sub-categories for this paper.
